{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\nBring the symmetric HMAC-SHA256 primitive (`src/rebar/signing.py`) into the attest scheme registry (`src/rebar/attest/registry.py`, task 518b) as a **first-class registry scheme** so the substrate acknowledges HMAC and both consumer epics reference one registry. This is the **expand** phase.\n\n**Scope boundary (deliberate).** Existing plan-review / completion-verifier attestations are stored in the *legacy* shape: a hex HMAC over the canonical `{v,algorithm,ticket_id,manifest}` payload, in the record `signature` field â€” NOT a DSSE envelope. This leaf does **NOT** reroute those old records through the registry; they keep verifying **unchanged** through the untouched `signing.py` path. What this leaf adds is (a) an `HmacScheme` registered in the registry (so HMAC is a known scheme, keyed by its algorithm id) and (b) `POLICY` entries pinning the legacy kinds to it. The HMAC->asymmetric cutover and any re-enveloping of old records is the op-cert epic contract phase, out of scope here.\n\n## Contract (concrete)\n- `HmacScheme` implements the registry `Scheme` protocol; `name = signing.ALGORITHM` (`\"HMAC-SHA256\"`).\n- `HmacScheme.verify(pae_bytes, signatures, namespace, trust_root) -> registry.Verdict` computes HMAC-SHA256 over `pae_bytes` (the DSSE-PAE bytes) using the key supplied as `trust_root` and constant-time-compares (`hmac.compare_digest`) to `signatures[0].sig` (the raw bytes of the first `dsse.Signature`). Result: match -> `Verdict(True,\"certified\",...)`; non-match -> `Verdict(False,\"mismatch\",...)`; empty/missing key -> fail closed `Verdict(False,\"foreign_key\",...)`; no signatures -> `Verdict(False,\"mismatch\",...)`.\n- `register_legacy_schemes()` is **idempotent**: registers the `HmacScheme` and pins `POLICY[\"plan-review\"]` and `POLICY[\"completion-verifier\"]` to `Policy(scheme=\"HMAC-SHA256\", namespace=\"rebar-attest-hmac\")`. Called once from `src/rebar/attest/__init__.py` at import.\n\n## Files\n- `src/rebar/attest/hmac_legacy.py` â€” `HmacScheme` + `register_legacy_schemes()`.\n- `src/rebar/attest/__init__.py` â€” call `register_legacy_schemes()` at import.\n- `src/rebar/signing.py` â€” **UNCHANGED** (regression guard).\n- `tests/unit/test_attest_hmac_legacy.py`.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] After import, `registry.get_scheme(\"HMAC-SHA256\")` returns the `HmacScheme`, and `registry.resolve(\"plan-review\").scheme == \"HMAC-SHA256\"` and `registry.resolve(\"completion-verifier\").scheme == \"HMAC-SHA256\"` (both pinned to namespace `rebar-attest-hmac`) â€” test asserts all four.\n- [ ] `HmacScheme.verify` fail-closed matrix over DSSE-PAE bytes: correct key -> `certified`; wrong key -> `mismatch`; empty key -> `foreign_key`; empty signatures list -> not certified. A round-trip helper builds `signatures[0].sig = hmac_sha256(key, pae_bytes)` to prove the certified path.\n- [ ] `register_legacy_schemes()` is idempotent â€” calling it twice leaves exactly one `HMAC-SHA256` scheme and the same two POLICY entries (test).\n- [ ] Regression / no-behavior-change: a plan-review manifest signed via `signing.sign_manifest` still returns `verdict == \"certified\"` from `signing.verify_signature`, and `src/rebar/signing.py` sign/verify functions are not modified by this change (test signs+verifies exactly as before and gets `certified`)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783787380877084001,"uuid":"4244b7e5-bff9-4148-af42-7b2a4cfc21df"}